# 🛡️ BluAgent SOC Commander (RUFLO)

> **A full-spectrum, 36-role AI-powered Security Operations Center that turns Claude into a coordinated team of cybersecurity specialists — triaging alerts, coordinating incident response, reversing malware, hunting threats, and generating forensic-grade reporting, all from a single prompt. Engineered with a three-tier token architecture so that even when 8 specialists fire in parallel, your context window stays efficient.**

---

## Why SOC Commander Exists

Modern Security Operations Centers require deep, specialized expertise across a dozen disciplines simultaneously. Tier 1 triage. Memory forensics. Malware reverse engineering. Threat intelligence correlation. Detection engineering. OSINT investigation. Most AI security tools give you a single generalist response. That's not how real SOCs work.

**SOC Commander is different.** It activates a structured orchestration layer — a Master Orchestrator backed by 36 specialist roles — that mirrors how an enterprise SOC actually operates. You get routed, structured, expert-level responses from the right specialist for the right task, with escalation chains, multi-role parallel workflows, and output formatted for actual incident operations.

Built for mid-market security teams, MSSPs, vCISOs, GRC practitioners, and security researchers who need elite SOC-grade AI output without enterprise headcount.

---

## What's RUFLO?

**RUFLO** is the internal project name and zip distribution format for this skill set: `BluAgent-SOC-Ruflo.zip`. It represents the full packaged release of the SOC Commander skill tree — the Master Orchestrator plus all 36 specialist roles across 16 discipline folders, structured for installation into Claude's skill system.

When you see references to RUFLO in issues, PRs, or internal BluAgent tooling, it refers to this complete skill bundle.

---

## What It Does

SOC Commander activates when you present:

- Raw security alerts, SIEM events, or firewall/EDR logs
- Active incidents ("We're seeing lateral movement on a DC")
- Artifacts for analysis (malware samples, PCAPs, memory dumps, IOCs, email headers)
- Threat hunting requests
- Detection engineering tasks (new Sigma/KQL/SPL/YARA rules)
- Compliance and GRC security questions with framework mapping
- Vulnerability assessment and prioritization
- Post-incident documentation and forensic reporting

The **SOC Commander (Master Orchestrator)** receives your input, classifies it, assesses severity, and routes it to the correct specialist — or coordinates multiple specialists in parallel for complex incidents.

---

## The Three-Tier Token Architecture

> **This is one of SOC Commander's most important engineering decisions.** With 36 role files across 16 folders, naively loading all specialists into context simultaneously would saturate the context window before you've typed a single alert.

SOC Commander uses a **three-tier lazy-loading model** that keeps token utilization lean regardless of how many roles are invoked.

### Tier 1 — Always in Context: Skill Descriptor (~100 words per skill)

Only the `name` and `description` fields from each skill's YAML frontmatter are loaded at all times. These are short (~100 words per role) and collectively establish the full roster without loading any deep content.

```yaml
---
name: bluagent-soc-commander
description: >
  Full-spectrum SOC orchestration skill for BluAgent. Activates a 36-role
  Security Operations Center with a Master Orchestrator...
---
```

### Tier 2 — Loaded on Trigger: Role SKILL.md (~50 lines)

When a specialist is invoked, only their `SKILL.md` loads — a **lean role file** containing identity, core responsibilities, and pointers to reference sub-files. These are intentionally kept to ~50 lines. No deep content lives here.

```
10-red-team/
├── red-team-lead.md       ← identity + responsibilities + pointers (~50 lines)
└── references/
    ├── engagement-planning.md
    ├── roe-template.md
    └── report-template.md
```

### Tier 3 — Loaded on Demand: Reference Sub-Files

Deep content — framework mappings, output templates, decision trees, evidence checklists, playbook steps — lives in `references/` sub-folders. These only load when explicitly needed by the specialist during task execution.

### Why This Matters at Scale

In a ransomware scenario where 8 specialists fire simultaneously:

| Approach | Token Load |
|---|---|
| Naïve — all content in each SKILL.md | 8 × ~300 lines = **2,400 lines** in context |
| Three-tier architecture | 8 × ~50 lines = **400 lines** + only needed references |

**The three-tier model reduces parallel-specialist token load by ~80% in complex multi-role scenarios.** This is what makes a 36-role SOC viable in a single context window.

### Design Rule Enforced Across All 36 Roles

No deep content (templates, decision trees, framework mappings, evidence checklists) lives directly in a role's `SKILL.md`. All heavy content is in `references/` sub-files and loads only when invoked by the specialist. This rule must be maintained for any new roles or contributions added to RUFLO.

